# Web components (Lit 3)

## Component layout

One folder per component: `src/components/<name>/` with:

- `<name>.ts` — Lit class and `@customElement`
- `<name>.css` — component styles (use theme tokens)
- `<name>.d.ts` — augment `HTMLElementTagNameMap` for the tag
- `<name>-types.ts` — exported type aliases and interfaces (property unions, event details, config shapes). Omit only if the component has zero consumer-facing types.
- `index.ts` — export class, re-export types, and side-effect import so the element registers

In `src/index.ts`: export each component class, re-export all public types, and side-effect import each component folder so all elements register when the library loads.

## Lit 3 + decorators

- Tag: `@customElement('app-<name>')` (must contain a hyphen; this repo uses `app-` prefix).
- Props: `@property()` for attributes; `@property({ attribute: false })` for callbacks (e.g. `onClick`).
- Class extends `LitElement`; use `override render()` and `static override styles = [unsafeCSS(componentCss)]`. Import CSS with `?inline`.

```ts
import { LitElement, html, unsafeCSS } from 'lit'
import { customElement, property } from 'lit/decorators.js'
import styles from './my-component.css?inline'

@customElement('app-my-component')
export class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  static override styles = [unsafeCSS(styles)]
  @property({ type: String }) label = ''
  override render() { return html`<span>${this.label}</span>` }
}
```

## Styling

- Component CSS: `import styles from './<name>.css?inline'` then `unsafeCSS(styles)` in `static override styles`.
- Use design tokens from `src/styles/theme.css` (e.g. `var(--color-primary)`, `var(--radius-button)`, `var(--ease-emphasized)`) so Shadow DOM stays themed.
- Use `:host` in component CSS for the host (e.g. `display: inline-block`).

## TypeScript

Add a `.d.ts` next to each component that augments `HTMLElementTagNameMap` so `querySelector` is typed:

```ts
import type { MyComponent } from './my-component'
declare global {
  interface HTMLElementTagNameMap { 'app-my-component': MyComponent }
}
```

## Type exports

Every component must export all consumer-facing types so library users can `import type { ... } from 'web-components'`.

1. **Create a `<name>-types.ts`** file next to the component `.ts` file. Put all exported type aliases and interfaces there (property union types, event detail interfaces, config objects, etc.). If a component only has types defined inline in the class, extract them into this file.
2. **Re-export from the component barrel** (`index.ts`):

```ts
export { MyComponent } from './my-component.ts'
export type { MyPropType, MyEventDetail } from './my-component-types.ts'
import './my-component.ts'
```

3. **Re-export from `src/index.ts`**:

```ts
export type { MyPropType, MyEventDetail } from './components/my-component'
```

Types to extract include:
- Union/literal types used for `@property()` values (e.g. variant, size, state enums).
- Interfaces for custom event `detail` payloads.
- Interfaces/types for complex property shapes (e.g. column definitions, menu items).

### No inline string literal unions on properties

Every string-literal union used to type a `@property()` **must** be a named `type` alias exported from `<name>-types.ts`. Never write the union inline on the class field.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — inline union
@property({ type: String })
variant: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost' = 'primary'

// ✅ GOOD — named type from types file
// in my-component-types.ts:
//   export type MyComponentVariant = 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost'
@property({ type: String })
variant: MyComponentVariant = 'primary'
```

## JSDoc

Every component **must** have JSDoc. This is required for new components and must be maintained when editing existing ones.

### Class-level JSDoc

Place directly above `@customElement(…)`. Include:
- One-sentence purpose.
- `@tag` — the custom element tag name.
- `@slot` — one entry per named slot (and the default slot if used). Format: `@slot name - Description.`
- `@fires` — one entry per custom event. Format: `@fires event-name - When it fires. Detail shape.`

```ts
/**
 * Text input with optional label, leading icon slot, and validation state.
 *
 * @tag app-input
 * @slot icon - Optional leading icon displayed before the input field.
 * @fires input - Native input event on value change.
 */
@customElement('app-input')
export class Input extends LitElement { … }
```

### Property-level JSDoc

Every public `@property()` and callback (`attribute: false`) must have a one-line JSDoc comment. Mention the HTML attribute name when it differs from the property name.

```ts
/** Visible label rendered above the input. */
@property({ type: String })
label = ''

/** Error text shown when `state` is `'invalid'` (attribute: `error-message`). */
@property({ type: String, attribute: 'error-message' })
errorMessage = ''

/** Callback invoked with the new value on every input event. Set via property. */
@property({ attribute: false })
onChange?: (value: string) => void
```

### Type-level JSDoc

Every exported type and interface in `<name>-types.ts` must have a one-line JSDoc comment. Interface members that are not self-explanatory should also be documented.

```ts
/** Allowed HTML input types for `<app-input>`. */
export type InputType = 'text' | 'email' | 'password' | …

/** Detail payload for the `selector-change` custom event. */
export interface SelectorChangeEventDetail {
  /** Selected values. Always an array. */
  value: string[]
}
```

## Build

Vite uses SWC with legacy decorators and `useDefineForClassFields: false`. Keep using `@property()` with initializers; do not rely on `useDefineForClassFields: true`.

## Accessibility (WCAG 2.2)

All components must meet WCAG 2.2 AA. Organize thinking by the four principles:

### Perceivable

- Decorative SVG/icons: always add `aria-hidden="true"`.
- Meaningful images/SVG: provide an accessible name via `aria-label` on the element or a `<title>` inside the SVG.
- Never convey information by color alone — pair color with text, icon, or pattern.
- Color contrast: normal text ≥ 4.5 : 1, large text / UI components ≥ 3 : 1. Always use `var(--color-*)` tokens so theming stays compliant.

### Operable

- **Keyboard**: every interactive element must be reachable via Tab and operable with Enter/Space. Custom elements must not swallow keyboard events without re-dispatching them.
- **Focus indicator** (2.4.11 — new in WCAG 2.2): `:focus-visible` outline ≥ 2 px solid, contrast ≥ 3 : 1 against adjacent background. Shadow DOM must declare this in the component CSS:

```css
/* in component CSS */
button:focus-visible,
input:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--color-focus);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}
```

- **Target size** (2.5.8 — new in WCAG 2.2): interactive targets ≥ 24 × 24 CSS px. Prefer ≥ 44 × 44 px for primary actions.
- **No keyboard trap**: modal-like panels (e.g. column-toggle) must close on Escape. Wire this in `connectedCallback`/`disconnectedCallback`:

```ts
connectedCallback() {
  super.connectedCallback()
  this.addEventListener('keydown', this._handleKeydown)
}
disconnectedCallback() {
  super.disconnectedCallback()
  this.removeEventListener('keydown', this._handleKeydown)
}
private _handleKeydown = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
  if (e.key === 'Escape') this._togglePanelOpen = false
}
```

### Understandable

- Buttons must always have an accessible name. Icon-only buttons must set `aria-label`:

```ts
// ✅ icon-only
html`<button aria-label="Delete row"><svg aria-hidden="true">…</svg></button>`
// ✅ labelled by visible text — no aria-label needed
html`<button><svg aria-hidden="true">…</svg> Delete row</button>`
```

- Communicate dynamic state changes with ARIA: `aria-sort` on sortable headers, `aria-expanded` on disclosure buttons, `aria-current="page"` on active pagination buttons.
- Add a live region for content that updates in place (e.g. pagination count) so screen readers announce the change:

```ts
html`<span aria-live="polite" class="sr-only">
  Page ${this._page} of ${this._totalPages}
</span>`
```

- Include a visually-hidden utility class in component CSS when needed:

```css
.sr-only {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px; height: 1px;
  padding: 0; margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0 0 0 0);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;
}
```

### Robust

- Prefer native semantics (`<button>`, `<table>`, `<th scope="col">`, `<nav>`) over custom `role=` attributes.
- When a custom `role` is required, always include its mandatory ARIA states/properties (e.g. `role="menuitemcheckbox"` requires `aria-checked`).
- Validate component markup with axe-core or Playwright accessibility checks in CI.
